<item>
            <title>[CXF-9111] Default behavior for &quot;multipart/form-data&quot; requests not standard-conform</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CXF-9111</link>
                <project id="12310511" key="CXF">CXF</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;We are using a client interface like this:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&#160; &#160; @POST
&#160; &#160; @Path(&quot;/checkMultipartAsAttachment&quot;)
&#160; &#160; @Consumes(MediaType.MULTIPART_FORM_DATA)
&#160; &#160; void checkMultipartAsObject(@Multipart(value = &quot;part1&quot;, type = MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON) JsonData part1, &#160;@Multipart(value = &quot;part1&quot;, type = MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON) JsonData part2);&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, the multiparts are not recognized by e.g. Spring MVC. When inspecting the internal CXF data structures, I can see that the generated Attachment objects have no Content-Disposition header, and thus, no Content-Disposition header is sent through the wire.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Instead, a &quot;Content-ID&quot; header is sent. This header is also picked up by CXF on server-side, so CXF-&amp;gt;CXF communication works.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;As far as I can tell, the currently generated request is not valid for MIME type &quot;multipart/form-data&quot; according to the relevant &lt;a href=&quot;https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7578&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7578&lt;/a&gt; .&lt;br/&gt;
(it might by valid for MIME type &quot;multipart/related&quot; according to &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2387.txt&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2387.txt&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The same holds true by default for requests like this:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&#160; &#160; @POST
&#160; &#160; @Path(&quot;/checkMultipartAsAttachment&quot;)
&#160; &#160; @Consumes(MediaType.MULTIPART_FORM_DATA)
&#160; &#160; void checkMultipartAsAttachment(Attachment multipart);
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, in these cases we could at least add the Content-Disposition Header to the Attachment-object in our own code.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It would be great if by default, requests for &quot;multipart/form-data&quot; would be standards-conform.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
